    "text": "The primary visualization on this page is a Decomposition Tree, a powerful analytical tool that allows us to break down a high-level metric—in this case, the Total Amount Claimed—into granular, nested categories.\n\n\nThe model operates as a “Root Cause” flow. By selecting a high-level branch, you can see exactly how that value is distributed across lower levels:\n\nTotal Amount Claimed ($375,726.32): This is the “Root.” It represents the total financial footprint of the selected dataset.\nClinical Driver (Disease Description): The first split identifies which diagnoses are driving the most costs. For example, Viral Sinusitis and Acute Bronchitis appear as major financial contributors.\nGeographic Node (City): By clicking a disease, the tree branches into locations. This tells us where these cases are being treated (e.g., Boston, Brookline, Quincy).\nThe Final Payer: The terminal branch identifies the specific insurance provider (or the lack thereof) responsible for that specific clinical-geographic path.\n\n\n\n\nDecomposition Tree Analysis"
