    "section": "Critical Data Awareness: Understanding the Skews",
    "text": "Critical Data Awareness: Understanding the Skews\nTo ensure this model is used responsibly, we must acknowledge two significant “skews” present in the current dataset. These are not errors in the visualization, but reflections of the underlying data distribution.\n\n1. The Boston Geographic Centroid\nA significant portion of the patient data in this database is centered around Boston. * The Impact: In our tree, Boston appears as a dominant force in almost every clinical path. * The Risk: It is important to distinguish between a “Boston health trend” and a “data volume skew.” This model is urban-heavy; it assumes high access to medical facilities and high encounter rates that may not exist in rural Massachusetts. —"
