    "text": "The existant Racial Gap proven with this model\nWhen drilling down into race-based demographics, the data reveals a stark reality regarding healthcare access: * Coverage Disparity: The dataset shows that White populations have significantly higher insurance coverage rates and more documented clinical encounters. * The “No Insurance” Branch: Minorities (including Black, Asian, and Native American demographics) are disproportionately likely to fall into the “No Insurance” or “Medicaid” branches of the tree. * The Narrative Risk: If we ignore this skew, we might assume certain demographics “need less care” simply because they have less data. In reality, the lack of data is often a direct result of a lack of insurance coverage.\nFinal Summary: This model is a masterclass in technical architecture and payer analytics. However, it should be viewed as a “snapshot of a system with existing gaps.” To turn this into clinical policy, we would first need to balance the dataset to represent rural populations and under-insured demographics more accurately."
